<h1>State buys 5 miles of pristine trout stream</h1>

<p><em>Plus: ID checks to use the bathroom at Colorado school, ski resorts preparing for climate change, decoding job numbers and more</em></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<p style="line-height:24px;"><span style="font-size:48px;line-height:12px;">G</span>ood morning, Colorado.</p>

<p>I&#8217;ve been hitting the snooze button more often than normal the past two days, but daylight saving time isn&#8217;t the only culprit. Over the weekend, I took a winter survival class near Kenosha Pass to learn how to best prepare if I were forced to stay overnight in the backcountry with only the gear in my day pack. At 10,115 feet, I learned to build different types of snow shelters (like a <a target="_blank"  href="https://scoutlife.org/outdoors/outdoorarticles/2992/how-to-build-a-quinzee-snow-shelter/">quinzee</a>), create a compass using the sun and pinecones, and how to start a fire in the snow, before hunkering down in my snow trench for the night.</p>

<p>As I crawled out of my trench at the day&#8217;s first light, my eyes felt heavy and my body ached from all of the shoveling. But sometimes, it&#8217;s all worth it knowing you did something you weren&#8217;t sure you could do.</p>

<p>That being said, I&#8217;m grateful for my fuzzy slippers and hot coffee while I write this morning&#8217;s newsletter from the warmth of my home. Let&#8217;s get reading.</p>

