</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3>THE NEWS</h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h4>ENVIRONMENT</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-land-conservation-south-park-ranch-tarryall/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Colorado Parks and Wildlife lands a spectacular hunting and fishing ranch in South Park</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Collard_Ranch_Tarryall_Creek_CREDIT_Christi_Bode-scaled.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-land-conservation-south-park-ranch-tarryall/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p class="caption">Colorado Parks and Wildlife will transform the nearly 1,900-acre Collard Ranch in South Park into a state wildlife area, with five miles of fishing and wildlife preservation on Tarryall Creek one of the prime features. (Christi Bode, via Western Rivers Conservancy)</span></p>

<blockquote>&#8220;Land purchases, like everyone knows buying houses on the Front Range, is difficult to do, and we&#8217;re losing habitat in a lot of spaces. So an opportunity like this does not come up often. We&#8217;re really thrilled that it has gone our way.&#8221;<br><br><span class="pullquote-source">â€” Kara Van Hoose, spokesperson for Colorado Parks and Wildlife&#8217;s northeast region</span></blockquote>

<p>Calling all hunters and anglers â€” there&#8217;s a new state wildlife area to add to your list. Nearly 1,900 acres of stunning South Park fishing and hunting habitat will be turned into a new state wildlife area later this year after Great Outdoors Colorado funded most of the $8.25 million purchase of Collard Ranch on Tarryall Creek. Public access could begin &#8220;in months,&#8221; but in the meantime, <strong>Michael Booth </strong>has more details on the 5 miles of pristine trout stream and ranch that is known as a corridor for thousands of elk moving to and from the nearby mountains.</p>

<p><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-land-conservation-south-park-ranch-tarryall/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>READ MORE</strong></a></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<h4>WATER</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-ski-resorts-climate-change-eldora-mountain/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">How do Colorado ski resorts prepare for a changing climate? Ask Eldora Mountain Resort.</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/eldora-water-petersen-lake-1-scaled.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-ski-resorts-climate-change-eldora-mountain/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p class="caption">Peterson Lake on March 5, near Eldora Mountain Resort. The resort draws water from the lake for snowmaking on the slopes. (Olivia Sun, The Colorado Sun via Report for America)</span></p>

<p>Ski resorts may only take up a tiny slice of Colorado&#8217;s overall water use, but they&#8217;ll likely need to boost their supply by about 41% by 2050, according to state estimates. Eldora Mountain Resort is eyeing water storage sites to prepare for new ski runs and a drier future, and people opposed to the effort are requesting more transparency in their plans, <strong>Shannon Mullane</strong> reports.</p>

<p><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-ski-resorts-climate-change-eldora-mountain/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>READ MORE</strong></a></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<h4>HEALTH</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/medical-debt-colorado-law-health-care-costs/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Colorado leads on medical debt protections, even as health care costs remain &#8220;out of control&#8221;</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Vance-CA-01.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/medical-debt-colorado-law-health-care-costs/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p class="caption">Lindsey Vance poses for a portrait Sunday at her home in Denver. (Chloe Anderson, Colorado Newsline)</span></p>

<p>For nearly half her life, Lindsay Vance has carried medical debt. It began stacking up when she was 19 and has prevented her from having a car, an apartment and credit cards in her name for most of her adult life. A newly enacted law aims to help the 700,000 Coloradans like Vance by removing medical debt from consumer credit reports. <strong>Sara Wilson</strong> digs into the legislation that is putting Colorado at the forefront of the issue.</p>

<p><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/medical-debt-colorado-law-health-care-costs/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>READ MORE</strong></a></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<h4>EDUCATION</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-school-bathroom-policy-eagle-ridge-academy-brighton/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Need to use the bathroom during class? At this Colorado school, students must first show their ID.</h2>

<p>Asking your teacher if you can step out for a bathroom break during class no longer requires simply raising your hand at Eagle Ridge Academy, a charter school in Brighton that now requires kids to show their student ID before dashing to the restroom. The school&#8217;s principal says the new policy seeks to cut down on loitering and vandalism, but many students are frustrated, saying they are sometimes forced to wait several hours for the restroom. <strong>Erica Breunlin </strong>has more.</p>

<p><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-school-bathroom-policy-eagle-ridge-academy-brighton/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>READ MORE</strong></a></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<h4>BUSINESS</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-unemployment-rate-job-growth-2023/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Why Colorado had higher unemployment rates but more job growth in 2023 than the Feds reported</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2024-03-12-at-08.42.49.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-unemployment-rate-job-growth-2023/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text>

<p>Colorado&#8217;s labor market last year wasn&#8217;t quite as sluggish as federal data estimated, <strong>Tamara Chuang </strong>reports. With stronger job growth and overall economic growth rates outpacing national averages, the latest revisions to the state&#8217;s numbers are painting a rosier picture.</p>

<p><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/12/colorado-unemployment-rate-job-growth-2023/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>READ MORE</strong></a><strong>, </strong><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/podcast/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>HEAR MORE IN TODAY&#8217;S SUN-UP PODCAST</strong></a></p>

