</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3>SunLit</h3></mj-text>
<mj-image width="300" src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Disneyland-cover.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/10/sunlit-disneyland-on-the-mountain-greg-glasgow-kathryn-mayer/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/10/sunlit-disneyland-on-the-mountain-greg-glasgow-kathryn-mayer/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">&#8220;Disneyland on the Mountain&#8221; recounts a high-profile tussle for development rights</h2>

<p>At a time when Walt Disney exercised tremendous influence on American culture, he and his company set their sights on developing a massive ski area in California&#8217;s Mineral King Valley. Co-authors and spouses <strong>Kathryn Mayer</strong> and <strong>Greg Glasgow</strong> couldn&#8217;t believe no one had written a book about the competition for what turned out to be an ill-fated bid â€” and the fledgling environmental movement that mobilized to stop it. So they wrote it themselves, and in this week&#8217;s excerpt describe the beginnings of the star-studded effort that stretched for more than a decade.</p>

<p><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/10/sunlit-disneyland-on-the-mountain-greg-glasgow-kathryn-mayer/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>READ AN EXCERPT</strong></a></p>

<ul><li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/10/sunlit-greg-glasgow-kathryn-mayer-disneyland-on-the-mountain/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>Interview with the co-authors.</strong></a> Mayer and Glasgow decided to run with their interest and research on the Disney effort, as well as the environmental movement that opposed it. And they found that a spousal writing duo has some advantages.</li>
</ul>

